@tylerbozinovski427 The founding fathers also specifically designed the Senate after England's House of Lords and the electoral college to make the popular vote entirely meaningless. In fact, the system was purposely designed for the votes to hang up without a winner, so their personally appointed-for-life Senate members could choose the President they wanted instead. Even the biggest proponents to fight for a Senate with equal state representation fully admitted at the time that they were doing so for entirely selfish reasons to give themselves, personally, more power, and that they'd be against it if they were from larger states. Much of this was later changed because they were bad ideas that ended up just not working. The founding fathers' ideas were not some perfect ideal, and should really stop being treated as such. They also weren't a monolith, and they all had extremely differing ideas about how things should be.

Rule by a minority is still mob rule, just from a different mob. Particularly with no real justification for why that particular minority should get all the deciding power, and when much of it has been gained through cheating the system. Saying popular vote shouldn't matter for this reason is basically saying that other people's votes shouldn't count solely because you personally disagree with them. Many people I see spout this will also go on to claim the system was rigged against them if they end up losing, because they don't actually care about a fair or just government, they just want their side to be on top. If they win, no matter how unfair the win, that's just how the system is supposed to work so you have to accept it, but if they lose, it's because the system is broken and needs to be "fixed".

So if you want to entirely disregard popular vote, you need an answer for who gets to decide which votes count, and how they do so. In a way people that end up losing will actually be able to accept. Which "the founding fathers wanted it that way" doesn't really do.

